This cartridge was developed as part of the Enhanced Rifle Cartridge Program in which U.S. Special Operations soldiers, as well as armorers and other technicians from the U.S. Army Marksmanship Unit, played a major role. Its primary purpose was to address the deficiencies in terminal performance seen with the 5.56x45mm NATO cartridge, while allowing the soldier to carry the same number of rounds with minimal weight penalty. It succeeds in doing so because it uses a heavier bullet with excellent accuracy, which delivers more energy across all effective ranges.

Until now, a major drawback of using the 6.8 cartridge in an M4 style weapon has been the lack of reliable magazines. So, when we designed the SIX8™ family of weapons, we started with the magazine. Building upon the magazine, we designed the SIX8™ platform for maximum reliability and improved ergonomics. The upper and lower receivers are designed to accommodate the slightly larger polymer magazine and to perfect the feed geometry for the 6.8 cartridge. In addition, we have prompted Federal Ammunition to develop new lines of affordably priced, high performance 6.8 ammunition for commercial, law enforcement and military applications.

As with the IC family, the weapons in the new SIX8™ family are fully ambidextrous and equally suited to right- or left-handed operators. The SIX8™ rifles are based on the familiar Stoner M4/AR15/M16 architecture, but they have been optimized specifically for use with the 6.8 cartridge.

The new SIX8™ family combines the ultimate in ergonomic user-friendly rifles with the outstanding mid-range 6.8 cartridge.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Walther P22
postcontent:
Walther has a rich tradition of creating quality firearms, and the P22 pistol is no exception. Known for its compact size (the short barrel is just 3.4 inches long), customizable features and contoured frames, the P22 is a tactical pistol that target shooters, law enforcement and civilians can enjoy. Many P22 styles are available, and thanks to features like removable grip back straps and extended magazines, the firearm can be customized to fit the needs of the owner.

The .22 rimfire handgun will never look the same. The P22 changed everything. Walther adapted the tactical styling and Performance Design concepts from their centerfire handguns and applied them to the .22 L.R. This created a new movement in the design of contemporary rimfire handguns ... and an explosion of imitators. As a stylish, fun gun to own, the P22 is at home on the shooting range, around the camp or in a museum of modern art.

This Walther P22 comes with the original box. It also has a laser, lock, and two magazines. I can also throw in some bullets if you'd like.

title: For Sale:  Colt Model 1917 in 45 ACP
postcontent: This Colt 1917 comes in 45 ACP and it is a DA/SA revolver. This handgun gun requires the use of half moon clips to get maximum shootability from it (ease of loading and emptying). You can shoot without these clips but you will have to poke the emptys out with a pencil or stick. These pistols were issued to the military during WW1 to aleviate the shortage of 1911 pistols. The govt. required them to be of the same caliber as the 1911, hence the use of half moon clips. It has a wartime blued finish. This pistol is in good condition and but exhibits some wear, the grips are walnut and also show some wear. These pistols are very collectable and comes with a holster(somewhat worn and not US GI) and a box of 100 rds of Federal ammo.It also comes with some half moon clips.

It still has the original white paint and the bluing is in excellent condition. I'd describe the stock as very good and it also includes the original sling. The only downside is the bore is dark with fair pitting, however the groves are still strong. I can also include 75rds of Yugo surplus, 20rds of PPU SP, 5 nickel plated stripper clips, 100 196 Privi bullets, 14 Peters SP bullets, 35 pieces of brass, and a set of once used RCBS 8mm neck reloading dies. title: For Sale:  Beautiful Stainless Colt King Cobra 4" Excellent Condition
postcontent:
After having collected all of the Colt 'snake' pistols, I've slowly been selling them off over the last 10 years or so.  This is my very LAST one.  Although not the most expensive by far, it has been my favorite.  I probably have the box somewhere, but the last time I saw it was more than 15 years ago.  Based on that fact, I'm just selling the pistol itself in a padded case.

I really don't have much I can add to this pistol except that is an all original Colt King Cobra .357 Magnum in Stainless Steel with a 4" barrel.  It has been fired, but not by me and I've owned it for around 20 years.  There is a slight mark on the cylinder from where it has turned.  I believe I could easily buff it out, but in my personal opinion, I'd rather have a collectable firearm that has not been tinkered with in any way.  Based on close observation, I seriously doubt this pistol was ever carried.  The leading edges are just too crisp.  There are no marks on the under lug at all.

If you have any questions, just ask.  Any sale must take place face to face in IN and I strongly prefer you have a license to carry.  If the sale is out of state, the purchaser will be responsible to pay actual shipping costs to their FFL dealer and, if their FFL dealer will not accept firearms from an individual, an additional $25 to have my local FFL dealer ship it to your FFL dealer.  These are some of the best pistols out there and are certainly excellent investments.
